ðŸ”¥ Example: Sign-in Location Heatmap (World Map)

SigninLogs
| where ResultType == 0
| summarize EventCount = count() by Location, bin(TimeGenerated, 1d)
| project Location, EventCount
| render map

But if you want actual lat/lon plotting, you need to break the Location field downâ€”or enrich it with GeoIP if Sentinel didnâ€™t give you that out of the box. Or use ip_to_geo() if your workspace supports it:


---

ðŸŒ Sign-in Map by IP (Using ip_to_geo())

SigninLogs
| extend geoInfo = ip_to_geo(IPAddress)
| where isnotempty(geoInfo)
| summarize count() by geoInfo.Country, geoInfo.City, geoInfo.Latitude, geoInfo.Longitude
| project City=geoInfo.City, Country=geoInfo.Country, Latitude=geoInfo.Latitude, Longitude=geoInfo.Longitude, Logins=count_
| render map

> ðŸ§  Pro tip: You canâ€™t render map unless youâ€™re in a Workbook or Logs blade that supports visual output. Pure alert rules won't show visuals, but hunting dashboards? Hell yes.




---

ðŸ§¬ Want a heatmap of internal east-west traffic?

Youâ€™ll need data like from NSG flow logs, Zscaler, or any 3rd-party firewall. Hereâ€™s an idea for volume between internal IPs:

AzureNetworkAnalytics_CL
| where FlowDirection_s == "Inbound"
| summarize TotalBytes = sum(BytesTransferred_d) by SrcIP_s, DstIP_s
| project SrcIP=SrcIP_s, DstIP=DstIP_s, TotalBytes
| render heatmap

> Replace field names with your actual schemaâ€”because Microsoft loves 20 naming conventions.




